ity, performance, product sense, maintainability, and type safety. Focuses on CLI as primary area but covers all repo areas. Outputs inline comments at two severity levels: [request] (blocking) and [non-blocking] (high-bar only). Actively searches codebase for existing patterns before flagging duplication. Use when reviewing a PR or when asked to review code changes.\nask: Use this when you are exploring the codebase. It lets you ask the AI who wrote code questions about how things work and why they chose to build things the way they did. Think of it as asking the engineer who wrote the code for help understanding it.\nprompt-analysis: Analyze AI prompting patterns and acceptance rates\ngit-ai-search: Search and restore AI conversation context from git history\nfeng-shui: Architectural harmony assessment for your codebase.\nperformance-review: Annual performance review for your codebase.\ntherapy-session: Guided counseling session for your codebase.\ncobol-converter: COBOL migration plan with translated output.\nroast: Candid code review from an industry expert perspective.\nagent-repellent: Assess your codebase's resistance to AI-assisted development tools.\nobituary: Retrospective on deprecated and end-of-life code.\nblame: Git history investigation surfacing patterns and anomalies.\ndating-profile: Compatibility profile based on technology stack and architecture.\nship-ritual: Pre-deployment blessing for your next release.\n\nProactively invoke a listed skill when the user's request warrants specialized instructions or would benefit from that skill's domain knowledge.\n</system-reminder>",
